I am applying for the Lecturer position of the Applied Economics Section of the Utrecht University School of Economics.
Currently, I am a PhD candidate in Economics at Southern Methodist University, specializing in Applied Microeconomics with an emphasis on Culture and Gender Economics, and I expect to complete my degree by May 2026.

As a Spanish national, my family and I are eager to return to Europe so our newborn daughter can grow up immersed in European culture. We are seeking a community with a safe learning environment, a key factor in our decision to leave the United States.

My job market paper provides causal evidence that teenage exposure to telenovelas featuring empowered female characters increases women's subsequent labor force participation.
The effects are driven exclusively by portrayals of women in non-traditional careers and narratives that frame empowerment with joy or anger.
A second paper shows that telenovelas focused on inequality reduce support for redistribution by downplaying or trivializing issues of economic disparity.
My research applies advanced econometric techniques to estimate the causal effects of media exposure on attitudes and behaviors. Additionally, I use generative AI and natural language processing to analyze cultural values, demonstrating my experience in employing innovative methodologies and managing large datasets in economic research.

My commitment to leveraging innovative methodologies aligns closely with Utrecht University's ambition to catalyze societal change through interdisciplinary, applied research. For example, my application of generative AI to analyze cultural values in television shows exemplifies the department's methodological strengths in data science and econometrics, directly contributing to policy-relevant topics such as labor market dynamics and inequality. Through mentoring student athletes, I have developed a teaching approach that fosters engagement and independence, reflecting the faculty's emphasis on inspiring and supporting students' academic and practical growth. I am eager to contribute to the Economics Department team through teaching the next generation of economists.
